## Model Routing Strategy

Exodus uses a two-tier routing architecture: **cloud** (Anthropic) for quality-sensitive tasks, **local** (Ollama on Mac Studio) for speed and cost efficiency. All routing goes through `exodus-core` LLM router — never call APIs directly in product code.

### Cloud Models (Anthropic)

| Task | Model | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Writing new code from scratch | **opus** | Maximum quality, architectural reasoning |
| System / schema design, ADRs | **opus** | Complex multi-constraint reasoning |
| Security analysis | **opus** | Must not miss subtle issues |
| Data modeling (dbt, Kimball) | **opus** | Business logic fidelity |
| PEVR planning phase | **opus** | Plan quality determines implementation quality |
| PR review pass 2 (escalated) | **opus** | Deep review when pass 1 flags BLOCK candidates |
| PR review pass 1, standard review | **sonnet** | Reliable quality at standard cost |
| Test generation | **sonnet** | Coverage and edge case reasoning |
| Refactoring, documentation | **sonnet** | Good quality, not max-quality |
| Data diff, NL-to-SQL | **sonnet** | Sufficient for standard complexity |
| Confidence scoring, routing decisions | **haiku** | Fast, cheap, accurate for simple decisions |
| Commit message validation | **haiku** | Pattern matching |
| Metadata extraction | **haiku** | Extraction tasks, not reasoning |

### Local Models (Ollama — Mac Studio M4 Max)

| Task | Model | VRAM |
|---|---|---|
| Code generation, PR review pass 1 | **qwen2.5-coder:32b** | 20 GB |
| Feedback loops, root cause analysis | **qwq:32b** | 20 GB |
| YAML config, lightweight code | **qwen2.5-coder:14b** | 9 GB |
| Task classification, routing | **qwen2.5-coder:7b** | 5 GB |
| Local embeddings | **nomic-embed-text** | 0.3 GB |

### Routing Rules

- **Premium tier → opus:** architectural decisions, security, new code from scratch, planning
- **Standard tier → sonnet OR qwen2.5-coder:32b:** code review, test gen, refactoring
- **Economy tier → haiku OR qwen2.5-coder:7b:** classification, pattern matching, extraction

**Two-pass PR review logic:**
1. Pass 1 (always): `qwen2.5-coder:32b` locally — fast, zero API cost
2. Pass 2 (conditional): `claude-opus-4` — only when pass 1 confidence < 70% or BLOCK candidate detected

**Never:**
- Use opus for classification, linting, or formatting — wastes budget
- Use haiku or 7b for code generation or security review — insufficient quality
- Hardcode model names in product code — use `exodus-core` router + tier constants

### In Code

```python
from exodus_core.llm import LLMRouter, ModelTier

router = LLMRouter()

# Cloud routing
response = router.call(prompt, tier=ModelTier.PREMIUM)   # opus
response = router.call(prompt, tier=ModelTier.STANDARD)  # sonnet
response = router.call(prompt, tier=ModelTier.ECONOMY)   # haiku

# Local-first routing (falls back to cloud if Mac Studio unreachable)
response = router.call(prompt, tier=ModelTier.STANDARD, prefer_local=True)
# → qwen2.5-coder:32b if OLLAMA_BASE_URL reachable, else sonnet
```

### Upgrading Models

When Anthropic releases new Claude versions or Ollama publishes better models:
1. Update `ai/model-routing.yml` family aliases only
2. Run `make sync-ai` to propagate to all repos
3. Never update individual agent files — the router resolves aliases
